, finished polities, Sarah Hogan makes the case that utopian literature offered readers and writers a transformational and transitional social imaginary. She shows how a genre associated with imagining systemic alternatives both contested and contributed to the ideological construction of capitalist imperialism. In the early English utopia, she finds both a precursor to the Enlightenment discourse of political economy and another historical perspective on the beginnings and enduring conflicts of global capital.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCapitalism in literature. 0aEnglish fictionyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aUtopias in literature. 0aUtopiaszEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aUtopiaszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 4aMarxism. 4aThomas More. 4aUtopia. 4acolonialism. 4acultural materialism. 4aearly modern England. 4agenre studies. 4aorigin stories. 4aprimitive accumulation. 4atransition debates. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360613540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503606135423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503606135.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles